"Text":"Battlezone (rev 2)\r\nCopyright 1980 Atari, Inc.\r\n\r\nBy Ed Rotberg, Jed Margolin, Harry Jenkins, Roger Hector, Howard Delman, Mike Albaugh, Dan Pliskin, Doug Snyder, Owen Rubin, and Morgan Hoff.\r\n*\r\nDisassembly by Andy McFadden, using 6502bench SourceGen v1.7.\r\nOriginally published 2020/05/23\r\nUpdated with source refs 2022/03/08\r\n\r\nHuge thanks to:\r\n + Simon Stapleton for his partial Battlezone disassembly.\r\n + Eric Smith for his work deciphering the vector processor and math box.\r\n + The various MAME contributors.\r\n + douglasgb et.al. in the arcade-museum.com forums.\r\n\r\nPOKEY register descriptions from https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/POKEY .\r\n\r\nThe binary used is a concatenation of the eight ROMs that are addressable by the 6502.  The AVG ROMs were placed at the end.\r\n\r\nAbout a year and a half after I finished this, the original rev 1 source code was posted on GitHub.  I updated the project file with some notes, including references to the source file names.\r\n*\r\nMemory map in a nutshell:\r\n\r\n  $0000-03ff: RAM (1KB)\r\n  $0800-1fff: various I/O, including math box\r\n  $2000-2fff: vector generator RAM (4KB)\r\n  $3000-3fff: vector generator ROM (4KB)\r\n  $5000-7fff: program ROM (12KB)\r\n\r\nI/O port definitions (primarily from MAME driver):\r\n\r\n  IN0 ($0800): KBDTSLCR\r\n    K=\"tied to a 3KHz clock\"\r\n    B=\"VG HALT\" bit, indicates VSM is busy\r\n    D=diagnostic step\r\n    T=self-test switch position (1=self-test mode)\r\n    S=slam switch (0=slam detected)\r\n    LCR=coin mechanism state (left/center/right chutes)\r\n\r\n  DSW0 ($0A00): LLBBMMTT\r\n    LL=language (00=English, 01=French, 10=German, 11=Spanish)\r\n    BB=bonus tank score (00=none, 01=15K/100K, 10=25K/100K, 11=50K/100K)\r\n    MM=missile appears at score (5K, 10K, 20K, 30K)\r\n    TT=number of starting tanks (value + 2)\r\n\r\n  DSW1 ($0C00): BBBCRRPP\r\n    BBB=bonus coins\r\n       000=no bonus coin\r\n       001=for every 2 coins, +1 coin\r\n       010=for every 4 coins, +1 coin\r\n       011=for every 4 coins, +2 coins\r\n       100=for every 5 coins, +1 coin\r\n    C=center coin mech x1/x2\r\n    RR=right coin mech x1/x4/x5/x6\r\n    PP=play cost\r\n       00=free play\r\n       01=1 coin for 2 plays\r\n       10=1 coin for 1 play\r\n       11=2 coins for 1 play\r\n\r\n  IN3/POKEY_ALLPOT: U21BLLRR\r\n    U=unused\r\n    2=start 2 (not used)\r\n    1=start 1\r\n    B=button pressed\r\n    LL=left joystick (00=middle, 01=back, 10=fwd)\r\n    RR=right joystick (00=middle, 01=back, 10=fwd)\r\n\r\n  DSOUND_CTRL ($1840):\r\n    $80: motor enable - 1=engine sound enabled\r\n    $40: start LED - controls LED on cabinet start button\r\n    $20: sound enable - 0=mute all sound (incl. POKEY)\r\n    $10: engine rev - 0=rev down, 1=rev up\r\n    $08: cannon fire volume - 0=soft 1=loud\r\n    $04: cannon fire enable - set to 1 while cannon sound playing\r\n    $02: explosion volume - 0=soft 1=loud\r\n    $01: explosion enable - set to 1 while explosion sound playing\r\n\r\n*\r\nOn the battlefield, when facing angle 0, +Z is forward and +X is to the left.  Increase the angle to turn left (counter-clockwise rotation).  After the View transform, the distance to an object directly in front of the viewer is determined by the Z coordinate.  This is a little different from typical GL/DX conventions.\r\n",
"BoxMode":true,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"12288":{
"Text":"Vector generator ROM.\r\n\r\nThe current version of SourceGen does not have a facility for decoding AVG commands into meaningful pseudo-opcodes.  See the web site associated with this project for the code used to generate the instruction comments.\r\n",
"BoxMode":true,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"7320":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws a pre-formed string in the language specified by the DIP switch configuration.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: string index\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"7380":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws a string from a table.  There are 24 pre-defined strings.\r\n\r\nEach table entry is a two-byte header followed by a DCI string.\r\n +00: absolute X position / 4\r\n +01: absolute Y position / 4\r\n +02: character data, with high bit set on last byte\r\n\r\nIf the X and Y position are both zero, the string is drawn at the current beam position.\r\n\r\nThe character set is:\r\n  \u0027 \u0027, 0-9, A-Z, \u0027 \u0027, \u0027-\u0027, \u0027(C)\u0027, \u0027(P)\u0027\r\n\r\nEach character value is 2x the character index, which allows us to use the value directly as an index into a table of 16-bit VJSR instructions.\r\n\r\nStrings with indices $00-12 are displayed at half size, strings $14-2e at full size.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  $3b: string data ptr, low\r\n  A-reg: string ptr, high\r\n  X-reg: string index * 2\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10640":{
"Text":"Set X-reg to N, where N is the highest bit set in A-reg.  For example, if you pass in $80, X-reg=7.\r\n\r\n(Was this code imported from something else?  Why not just pass value in?)\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10629":{
"Text":"\r\nInitiates a sound effect on audio channel 1 and/or 2.\r\n\r\nThe effect is chosen by setting a single bit in the A-reg.  Setting A-reg to zero causes the value in the stack pointer to be used instead (this does not appear to be used by Battlezone).\r\n\r\n  $01: ch1: radar ping\r\n  $02: ch1: collided with object\r\n  $04: ch2: quiet \"merp\"\r\n  $08: ch2: extra life notification (4 high-pitched beeps)\r\n  $10: ch2: new enemy alert (three boops)\r\n  $20: ch1: saucer hit (played in a loop while saucer fades out)\r\n  $40: ch1: saucer sound (played in a loop while saucer alive)\r\n  $80: ch1+2: nine notes from 1812 Overture\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: effect choice\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  A/X/Y preserved\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10956":{
"Text":"\r\nZeroes out memory and resets hardware.\r\n\r\nControl transfers here when the 6502 is reset.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10858":{
"Text":"\r\nOutputs a CNTR opcode.  Moves beam to center of screen.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"12282":{
"Text":"\r\nReset and interrupt vectors.  Note memory is mirrored, so these values also appear at $fffa-ffff, where the 6502 expects to find them.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1423":{
"Text":"\r\nHandle a non-maskable interrupt (NMI).\r\n\r\nFrom the MAME sources:\r\n  m_maincpu-\u003eset_periodic_int(... BZONE_CLOCK_3KHZ / 12))\r\nThat means we get interrupted 250x per second.\r\n\r\nThe NMI handler manages a number of things, including:\r\n - Handling coin drops and the \"start\" button.\r\n - Initializing state for a new game.\r\n - Flipping the AVG display/write pointers.\r\n - Initiating display updates.\r\n - Updating sound effects.\r\n\r\nThree counters are updated every time through:\r\n - $3a: counter, incremented every time.  Among other things, this is used to flash text, e.g. BVC to toggle state 4x/second, BPL to toggle state 2x/second.\r\n - $39: counter, incremented every 16 interrupts.  Used to pace the game update code, which runs at 250/16=15.625 fps.\r\n - $ed: counter, decremented from 6.  When it hits zero we restart the vector state machine, which was hopefully HALTed.  This causes a screen refresh every 250/6=41.7 fps.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"13296":{
"Text":"VJSRs to the instructions that draw glyphs.  Because these are all VJSRs, and the list is terminated with a VRTS, you can exercise the full set by calling the first entry.  (The self-test code does this.)\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"14213":{
"Text":"\r\nTable for computation of arctan(T), where T is an 8-bit fraction holding the tangent or 1/tangent.  The values are angles in the first octant.\r\n\r\nTo find the angle in a right triangle, you first compute tan(x)=opposite/adjacent.  Battlezone computes that with the absolute values of position deltas or, if opposite is bigger, adjacent/opposite.  The goal is to get a 0.8 fractional value.  That value is then used as an index into this table to get an angle from $00 to $20 (0 to 45 degrees).  The signs of the lengths and the choice of numerator (i.e. which side was longer) determine which octant the result is in.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2944":{
"Text":"\r\nWait for a result from the math box.\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  A-reg: MB result, low byte\r\n  X-reg/Y-reg preserved\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3703":{
"Text":"\r\nTable of sines.  There are 65 entries, representing the first quadrant (angles 0-90, inclusive).  Each entry is a 16-bit signed value:\r\n\r\n  sine_tab[n] = 32768 * sin(alpha)\r\n\r\nBecause this is only the first quadrant, all values are positive.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3683":{
"Text":"\r\nCalculates the value of sin(theta), where theta is an angle in the range [$00,$7f], representing [0,179] degrees.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: angle $00-7f\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  A-reg: sine value, low byte\r\n  X-reg: sine value, high byte\r\n  Y-reg preserved\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3659":{
"Text":"\r\nCalculates the value of cos(theta), where theta is an angle in the range [$00,$ff], representing [0,359] degrees.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: angle $00-ff\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  A-reg: cosine value, low byte\r\n  X-reg: cosine value, high byte\r\n  Y-reg preserved\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3662":{
"Text":"\r\nCalculates the value of sin(theta), where theta is an angle in the range [$00,$ff], representing [0,359] degrees.  Returns a signed 1.15 value.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: angle $00-ff\r\n  P flags set for load of angle\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  A-reg: sine value, low byte\r\n  X-reg: sine value, high byte\r\n  Y-reg preserved\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3402":{
"Text":"\r\nTransforms vertices of an entry in the visible object list to clip/screen coordinates.\r\n\r\nThe object center positions in the list have already been view-transformed.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: index of list entry to transform * 2\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"14478":{
"Text":"\r\nShape vertex data.\r\n\r\nThe first byte in each shape is the length of the data, in bytes, plus one.  This is followed by the list of vertices, which are signed 16-bit coordinates.\r\n\r\nJed Margolin\u0027s \"Unit Vector Math for 3D Graphics\" document defines a left-handed coordinate system with +X into the monitor, +Y to the right, and +Z up.  Using this system, the coordinates are stored in X, Y, Z order.  The SourceGen visualizers expect a left-handed system with +X right, +Y up, +Z into the screen, so a simple translation is required.\r\n\r\nThe shapes themselves are flipped about the X coordinate.  If you look at the logo shapes, all of the coordinates in \"Ba\" are positive, even though it\u0027s supposed to be left of center.  The visualizer negates the X coordinate to compensate.\r\n\r\nBecause the math box effectively halves the X/Z coordinates during the model transformation, the shapes here are all twice as wide as they should be.  This can be compensated for by halving X/Z or doubling Y.\r\n\r\nThe table holds 44 addresses, two of which are unused.  The largest shape has 26 vertices.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"13094":{
"Text":"Space character.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"12294":{
"Text":"\r\nVJSRs for eight-part landscape + moon.  Each landscape section is 512 units wide, covering half of the screen.  At most 3 sections will be needed.\r\n\r\nWhen the player faces angle 0, the reticle is just to the right of the moon.  So at that angle, landscape 0 covers the left half of the screen, landscape 1 covers the right.  Every $20 units of rotation lines up with the next section.\r\n\r\nNote the list is not terminated with a VRTS, so if you call here you will see the first section twice.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10862":{
"Text":"\r\nAppends a 16-bit value to the AVG command list.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: low byte\r\n  X-reg: high byte\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10870":{
"Text":"\r\nAdds (Y-reg + 1) to the AVG cmd pointer.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10883":{
"Text":"\r\nAdds a SCAL instruction to the command list.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: \u0027B\u0027 value (0-7)\r\n  Y-reg: \u0027L\u0027 value (0-255)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10781":{
"Text":"\r\nAppends CNTR and HALT instructions to the command list.  Call when the command list is finished for this frame.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10923":{
"Text":"\r\nAppends a \"long\" vector draw command (VECT) to the list.\r\n\r\nThis accesses zero page with an indexed instruction, but I don\u0027t see a way to execute here with a different value for X-reg.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  $01: 3-bit intensity\r\n  $04/05: 13-bit deltaX\r\n  $06/07: 13-bit deltaY\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11096":{
"Text":"Initialize high score table.  The score and the initials are 3 bytes each.  The loop goes from 29 to 2, stepping by 3.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"14474":{
"Text":"\r\nDetermines when missiles first appear, based on DSW0 setting: after 5000, 10000, 20000, or 30000 points.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11946":{
"Text":"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3164":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws an object.  Call after transforming vertices.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: object type (0-43)\r\n  $10: object index * 2\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10896":{
"Text":"\r\nLike VgVec8I, but we don\u0027t overwrite the intensity in $01.  Only used by self-test code.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10909":{
"Text":"Multiply Y coordinate by 4.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10894":{
"Text":"\r\nAppends a \"long\" vector draw command (VECT) to the list.\r\n\r\nThis takes deltaX/deltaY as signed 8-bit values, which are multiplied by 4.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: deltaX / 4\r\n  X-reg: deltaY / 4\r\n  Y-reg: intensity (upper 3 bits)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10890":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws a point.\r\n\r\nThe hardware requires this to be done with VECT rather than SVEC.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: intensity\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10881":{
"Text":"\r\nAppends a SCAL instruction to the command list.\r\n\r\nThe \u0027B\u0027 value sets the scale to 2^(1-B), so B=0 is double size, B=1 is normal size, B=2 is half size, etc.  The \u0027L\u0027 value is set to zero.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: \u0027B\u0027 value (0-7)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10830":{
"Text":"Common code for VJSR/VJMP output.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"9330":{
"Text":"\r\nAddresses of shape draw commands.\r\n\r\nDraw commands use a byte code where each byte has the form VVVVVCCC.  The top 5 bits are the vertex index (0-31), the bottom 3 are the command (0-7).\r\n\r\nThe commands are:\r\n\r\n  0 - draw point at vertex\r\n  1 - set intensity with vertex index value (overridden for saucer/logo)\r\n  2 - move without drawing\r\n  3 - move to center of screen, then move without drawing\r\n  4 - draw to vertex with intensity=1 (h/w uses intensity from STAT)\r\n  5 - draw scaled AVG commands from $347a (for projectile explosion)\r\n  6 - no-op\r\n\r\nThe list is terminated with $ff.  See the implementation at $5c5c.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3345":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws a vector to a transformed vertex.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: intensity (high 3 bits)\r\n  $08: index of vertex (* 8)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5101":{
"Text":"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10825":{
"Text":"\r\nAppends a VJMP to an address.  (Unused.)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10842":{
"Text":"\r\nAppends a VJSR instruction, taking an address ($2000-3fff) as argument.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: low byte of address\r\n  A-reg: high byte of address\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10851":{
"Text":"\r\nAppends a STAT opcode.  This has the form:\r\n\r\n  0110xEHI IIIICCCC\r\n\r\nThis sets the color and intensity.  IIII is a 4-bit intensity value that is used whenever the 3-bit intensity in VCTR or SVEC is set to 1.  CCCC is a color value not used by Battlezone.\r\n\r\nWhen E is 0, the clip window is set based on the current beam position and the values of the H/I flags.\r\n\r\n(The hand-written documentation says E works the other way around, but that\u0027s not how the code is using it.  MAME avgdvg.cpp avg_bzone_device::handler_6() seems to agree with me.)\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: low 3 bits of upper byte (EHI flags)\r\n  Y-reg: low byte (intensity and color)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"14470":{
"Text":"\r\nDetermines if and when bonus tanks are awarded, based on DSW0 setting.\r\n\r\nThis is the score minus one in BCD, so 15K/25K/50K is stored as $14/$24/$49.  A second bonus tank is awarded at 100K points, unless the value is $00, in which case no bonus tanks are awarded at all.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2234":{
"Text":"\r\nUpdates volcano particles.\r\n\r\n(Some ADCs are done without setting or clearing the carry.  FWIW, the carry flag is set when the function is first called.)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2241":{
"Text":"Create new particle, maybe.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2084":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws volcano particles.\r\n\r\nThe right side of the top of the volcano is at the right edge of segment N.  The particle source point is at angle $60.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: ($2a) (player facing, high byte)\r\n  $04: ($27) player facing, low byte\r\n  $06/07: adjusted horizon Y coordinate\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11282":{
"Text":"Play diagnostic sound.  From the Atari service manual:\r\n\r\n\"RAM FAILURE is indicated by a sequence of 1 to 10 tones. You will hear a short low tone for each good RAM chip, and a long high tone for a failing RAM chip. The test stops with the first failing RAM-chip pair (example: J2 and H2 are a pair).\"\r\n\r\nAt this point, the tone for the first zero-page RAM chip is in the X-reg, and the tone for the second is in the stack pointer.  The frequency values both end in 2 so that it can also be used as a counter.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11568":{
"Text":"\r\nGet \"diag step\" switch state from IN0.  The bit is set when the switch is not pressed.  (In MAME, the \u00279\u0027 key is bound to the switch.)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11764":{
"Text":"\r\nReport results.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11211":{
"Text":"\r\nSystem test, engaged by resetting the system with the test button enabled.\r\n\r\nCalled from the system reset code, which initializes RAM to zero before jumping here.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11655":{
"Text":"\r\nThis is a sequence of tests for the math box.  Each test item is 2-4 bytes.  The first byte has the form:\r\n\r\n  ELHIIIII\r\n    E=1 if this is the end of the test sequence\r\n    L=1 if we want to check the low byte of the result\r\n    H=1 if we want to check the high byte of the result\r\n    IIIII=register index to write to (0-31)\r\n\r\nThe second byte is the value that gets written to the specified register.  If \u0027L\u0027 is set, the next byte is the expected result low byte.  If \u0027H\u0027 is set, the next byte is the expected result high byte.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11521":{
"Text":"\r\nCompute a rolling XOR of $ff with the contents of each 2KB chunk.  Each section of ROM has been tweaked so that the final XOR value is zero, so no table of correct values is required (which allows you to replace ROMs individually without having to update the test code).  Search for \"checksum adj\" comments to see which bytes appear to be used for this.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11168":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws an N-digit BCD number.  Values are stored in zero page in little-endian order, so when drawing from left to right we want to start with the last byte.\r\n\r\nLeading zeroes are output as spaces.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: zero page location with BCD data\r\n  Y-reg: number of two-digit values to draw\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11166":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws a four-digit (two-byte) BCD number.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10793":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws a single digit, 0-9.\r\n\r\nIf we\u0027re drawing a score, we want to show \"15000\", not \"015000\".  This means we need to drop the leading zero sometimes.  The glyph for zero is $01, and the glyph for space is $00, so we can convert the \u00270\u0027 to \u0027 \u0027 simply by not adding 1.  If we see a nonzero digit we want to ensure that we print all future zeroes.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: number to draw (0-9)\r\n  Carry flag is set to get \"don\u0027t draw zero\" behavior\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  Carry flag is set if it was set initially and value was zero\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"13380":{
"Text":"Hexagonal \"circle\" for (C) and (P).",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"7312":{
"Text":"\r\nAddresses of language-specific functions that do an address lookup.\r\n\r\n(Could just store addresses of string index tables?)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11135":{
"Text":"\r\nPower-on high scores list.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"892":{
"Text":"Make space in the high score table.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"16302":{
"Text":"\r\nVelocities for the 6 chunks that fly when an enemy unit is destroyed.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"14506":{
"Text":"Shape $0e is the projectile explosion pattern.  It uses a special drawing mode that scales the AVG code at $347a.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"13434":{
"Text":"Projectile explosion, displayed when a projectile from the player or an enemy tank strikes something.  The pattern is scaled up over the course of a few frames.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2215":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws one segment of the landscape background.  Updates state.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: index of segment to draw, * 2\r\n  Beam positioned at background start\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  A-reg: index of next segment, * 2\r\n  Beam positioned at next background start\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1992":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws the background (mountains/moon, volcano particles, horizon line).\r\n\r\nThis is all 2D stuff, using screen coordinates.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  $01: 0 (intensity)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"13086":{
"Text":"\u0027O\u0027 and \u00270\u0027.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"13138":{
"Text":"\u0027S\u0027 and \u00275\u0027.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"12930":{
"Text":"\r\nCharacter glyphs.  Each glyph fits in a 16x24 cell whose origin is the bottom-left corner.  The beam will be left at the initial Y coordinate, 8 units to the right of the character cell.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2073":{
"Text":"Volcano particles are visible from angles $39 through $87.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2319":{
"Text":"Kill particles that hit the ground.  Remember that particles use coordinates relative to the origin point at the top of the volcano, which is at Y=+94, so the ground is at -94.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2301":{
"Text":"Update the particle\u0027s Y position.  The Y velocity decrements each time, giving particles a gravitational acceleration.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2345":{
"Text":"Update the X position.  Velocity does not change.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1192":{
"Text":"The rev1 ROM is slightly different from $54a8-543c.  The old ROM would draw one tank icon for every 100K points, up to 10.  This ROM only draws one.  It also staggers each high score line 4 pixels to the left.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"14090":{
"Text":"\r\nSelf-test pattern.  Starts by setting the clip window to (+520,+520), (-520,-520).  Draws a rectangle around the 1024x768 screen, then diagonal cross-hatches.  Finally draws a series of horizontal lines near the center.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"14072":{
"Text":"\r\nShattered windshield effect, all 8 parts.\r\n\r\nThe shape visualized here will look slightly wrong to experienced players, because it was drawn to cover the entire screen.  During the game, the top part of it is cut off by the radar / score display area.  (The radar area isn\u0027t drawn when the player is dead, but the window clip isn\u0027t changed.)\r\n\r\n(The code copies the first N VJSRs out.  It would have been easier to list the VJSRs in reverse order, and then just output a VJSR to the first element.)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"116":{
"Text":"The game is being played, either by the player or the attract-mode demo.\r\n\r\nSet window to play area (bottom 3/4 of screen).\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"473":{
"Text":"\r\nSets top-right clip to the edge of the screen.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1179":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws the high score list.\r\n\r\nEach score is a two-byte BCD value, to which \"000\" is appended.  So the score rolls over at 10 million.  Each score has 3 bytes for initials.  To make indexing easier, scores are stored in a field 3 bytes wide; the 3rd byte is never used.\r\n\r\nThe highest score appears first in memory.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1341":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws the string that indicates when bonus tanks are provided.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"489":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws windshield cracks of doom.  Also handles re-spawn of player.\r\n\r\nThe main loop calls here with a JMP, not a JSR.  We either JMP back into it or, if the game is over, into the high score code.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1603":{
"Text":"Start a new game.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4425":{
"Text":"\r\nComputes the absolute value of $08/09, negating it if its negative.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6160":{
"Text":"\r\nComputes the angle from the enemy unit (tank/missile) to the player.  Sets deltaZ/deltaX values as a side-effect.\r\n\r\n(i.e. a tank must rotate to this angle to fire at the player.)\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  A-reg: angle (0-255)\r\n  $08/09: abs(deltaZ)\r\n  $0a/0b: abs(deltaX)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6191":{
"Text":"Compute abs(player_z - enemy_z).",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6217":{
"Text":"We have the absolute value of zdiff and xdiff, with the sign bits encoded in the Y-reg.  Check to see if we\u0027re at a 45-degree angle, which would yield X/Z=1 (which doesn\u0027t fit in the low 8 bits of an 8.8 fixed-point value).  Note we\u0027re effectively using a 2D coordinate system where +Z is right and +X is up, so Z is the \"adjacent\" side.\r\n\r\nWe don\u0027t have to worry about division by zero unless two objects have the same position.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6243":{
"Text":"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6292":{
"Text":"The result is an 8.8 fixed-point value, which we know is in the range (1,0], so we just want the fraction.  The division routine uses R6=$0a, which causes it to do 10 iterations instead of 16, effectively right-shifting the 16-bit result 6x.  If we do two more right shifts we will have the fraction as an 8-bit value.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4094":{
"Text":"Add score for kill.  Note we reference \"score,x\" -- the enemy gets points every time they kill the player.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6581":{
"Text":"\r\nDetermines which type of enemy tank is active or should be created.  The determination is based on the number of missiles that have been launched at the player.\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  Carry clear for slow tank, set for super tank\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1386":{
"Text":"\r\nAdds a single character glyph to the command list.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: character index * 2\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1259":{
"Text":"Add a tank icon for scores \u003e= 100K.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1125":{
"Text":"\r\nApplies the state of the right joystick to update one letter of the player\u0027s initials during high score entry.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1015":{
"Text":"Check to see if the fire button is pressed *and* wasn\u0027t pressed last time.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"965":{
"Text":"\r\nEnter initials for high score list.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1067":{
"Text":"Print the initials entered so far.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1105":{
"Text":"Done with initials, update game mode.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1090":{
"Text":"\r\nSaves the player-entered initials into the high score list.  Called after the 3rd letter is set, or we time out.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1308":{
"Text":"Position the beam for the next entry.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1396":{
"Text":"\r\nPuts finishing touches on the current display frame.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"630":{
"Text":"Subtracts the first 54 command bytes from zero, then subtracts $75, yielding $01.  This value is then used when deducting credits, and after a few missiles have launched, to modify display rendering.  (See also $510a.)\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4447":{
"Text":"\r\nAwards a bonus tank if newly-awarded points cause the score to cross a threshold.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  $08/09: old score\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  X-reg: $00\r\n  Y-reg preserved\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4505":{
"Text":"\r\nInitializes flying chunks after an enemy unit is destroyed.  This sets the initial positions and Y velocity of the 6 chunks.\r\n\r\nThe positions and X/Z velocities are pre-determined.  The high byte of the initial Y velocity is fixed but the low byte is random.\r\n\r\nThe value in X-reg indicates the projectile\u0027s owner, not the exploding unit, so if it\u0027s not $00 there\u0027s nothing for us to do.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: $00 (player) or $02 (enemy)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5417":{
"Text":"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1687":{
"Text":"From the MAME sources:\r\n  m_screen-\u003eset_refresh_hz(BZONE_CLOCK_3KHZ / 12 / 6)\r\nRedrawing every 6 interrupts gives a 41.7 Hz refresh rate.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"0":{
"Text":"\r\nMain loop.\r\n\r\nA non-maskable interrupt fires at 250 Hz.  Every 16 interrupts the NMI handler increments the counter we\u0027re watching, which means we update the game state 15.625x per second.\r\n\r\nIf the NMI or non-NMI code locks up, the watchdog will eventually reset the machine.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1439":{
"Text":"If the N flag is set we\u0027ve overflowed the stack or the NMI x16 counter.  The counter will only overflow if the non-interrupt code is stuck.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1731":{
"Text":"\r\nCheck for coin drops.  We check each of the three bits in IN0 in turn.\r\n\r\n(this executes in the NMI context)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1912":{
"Text":" 001 = for every 2 coins, +1 coin\r\n 010 = for every 4 coins, +1 coin\r\n 011 = for every 4 coins, +2 coins\r\n 100 = for every 5 coins, +1 coin\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1884":{
"Text":"Check to see if the number of coins inserted entitles the player to a bonus coin (NOT a bonus credit).  The coin count in $ec is only used for this check, and is reset to zero when the game starts.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1920":{
"Text":"Compute the number of coins required for 1 credit.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1947":{
"Text":"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3652":{
"Text":"\r\nIf we have a nonzero horizon adjustment (caused by projectile impact or driving into something), reduce it toward zero.  Called once every game frame.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"16332":{
"Text":"\r\nObstacle type and facing data.\r\n\r\nEach entry is two bytes.  The first is the object type, the second is the facing angle.  (All obstacles are symmetric, so every 90-degree turn effectively returns to zero.)\r\n\r\nSee also the map position data at $7681 and the projectile collision diameters at $6139.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"665":{
"Text":"\r\nAdds the logo to the set of visible objects.  It\u0027s not part of the battlefield, just appended to the list.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3598":{
"Text":"Set the Y position for objects that aren\u0027t at ground level, notably missiles, the game logo, and chunks of exploding tanks.  We use 8 16-bit values to hold the height.  The height is assigned by object type rather than object index.\r\n\r\nTypes $10-15 and $18-1d are the exploding chunk types (6 pieces each), missiles are $16, logos use $17/1c/1d.  It would look really weird to show the logo and a missile at the same time.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"745":{
"Text":"Set the altitude for the logo objects, using the same mechanism used for missiles and exploding chunks.  The transform code sees that the object has type $1x and looks up the Y position from (type \u0026 7).\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3623":{
"Text":"Adjust object Y position with the horizon adjustment.  We\u0027re shifting the object Y positions by the same amount as the horizon, which isn\u0027t correct, but this is cheaper than rotation about the X axis.  Having a slightly discombobulated feel isn\u0027t a bad thing for an impact effect.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2454":{
"Text":"\r\nTry to add enemy unit to visibility list.  This must come first (Y-reg=0).\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3918":{
"Text":"\r\nChecks to see if the player\u0027s projectile has hit the enemy unit.\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  Carry set if collision\r\n  X-reg: $00\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"7280":{
"Text":"Move a projectile.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1596":{
"Text":"Check to see if the \"start\" button has been pressed.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1952":{
"Text":"\r\nDo things with the coin counter.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"836":{
"Text":"\r\nChecks to see if the current score has earned a place on the high scores list.  If it has, play sound effects and prepare for score entry.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1447":{
"Text":"Do some stuff with the coin counter.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1471":{
"Text":"Update POKEY sounds.\r\n\r\nThe saucer noises are looped, so we want to restart them whenever the channel goes quiet.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5033":{
"Text":"\r\nCopies the position of the player or the enemy unit to $c0-c3.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: $00 (player) or $02 (enemy)\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  X-reg preserved\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5050":{
"Text":"\r\nCopies the position of the player or the enemy unit from $c0-c3.  This is used to \"undo\" a move after colliding with an obstacle or opposing unit.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: $00 (player) or $02 (enemy)\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  X-reg preserved\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4607":{
"Text":"\r\nReads player controls (joysticks and fire button).\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: $00 (player)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6358":{
"Text":"\r\nChecks for collision between unit (player or enemy) and obstacles, then checks for a collision with the opposing unit.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: $00 for player, $02 for enemy unit\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  Carry flag set if collision found\r\n  A-reg: $00 for obstacle, $ff for opposing unit\r\n  X-reg preserved\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3931":{
"Text":"\r\nTests for a collision between a projectile and the opposing unit (i.e. player vs. enemy or enemy vs. player).\r\n\r\nUpdates the score if the projectile hit.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: projectile owner: $00 (player) or $02 (enemy)\r\n  Y-reg: projectile target: $02/$00 (opposite of X-reg)\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  MathBox R0/R1 set to projectile X/Z position\r\n  Carry set if collision\r\n  X-reg preserved\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2953":{
"Text":"\r\nUpdates the positions of the flying chunks that are created when an enemy unit is destroyed.  If the chunks are in the viewport, add them to the list of visible objects.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3048":{
"Text":"Simulate gravity by reducing Y velocity.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10681":{
"Text":"\r\nUpdates sound effects on POKEY channels 1/2.  Called every NMI (250Hz).\r\n\r\nThere are 4 streams of data, for AUDF1, AUDC1, AUDF2, and AUDC2.  Some things use F1/C1, some things use F2/C2, one thing uses both channels.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4165":{
"Text":"\r\nChecks to see if one of the projectiles has hit something (enemy unit, saucer, obstacle).\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"527":{
"Text":"We\u0027re done being dead; get busy living or pack it in.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"9857":{
"Text":"\r\nObstacle coordinates.  There are 21 of them.\r\n\r\nSee also the type/facing data at $3fcc and the projectile collision diameters at $6139.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2796":{
"Text":"Add all visible obstacles.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"345":{
"Text":"\r\nDraw score, remaining lives, and attract-mode strings.\r\n\r\n(Other bits of code JMP here when done, e.g. windshield crack and high score entry.  Seven locations in total.)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10340":{
"Text":"\r\nFor each sound effect, these are the indices into the SFX audio data table for the start of the stream that drives AUDF1, AUDC1, AUDF2, and AUDC2.  Zero values indicate the register is not used by this effect.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10699":{
"Text":"Both counters reached zero.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10749":{
"Text":"Duration hit zero, but more reps to go.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10374":{
"Text":"\r\nPOKEY audio has four channels, with two 8-bit I/O locations per channel (AUDFn and AUDCn).  The sound effects defined by this data are played on channels 1 and 2.\r\n\r\nThe AUDFn setting determines frequency.  Larger value == lower pitch.\r\n\r\nThe AUDCn value is NNNFVVVV, where N is a noise / distortion setting, F is \"forced volume-only output\" enable, and V is the volume level.\r\n\r\nIn the table below, each chunk has 4 values:\r\n +00 initial value\r\n +01 duration\r\n +03 increment\r\n +04 repetition count\r\n\r\nThe sound specified by the value is played until the duration reaches zero.  If the repetition count is nonzero, the value is increased or decreased by the increment, and the duration is reset.  When the repetition count reaches zero, the next chunk is loaded.  If the chunk has the value $00, the sequence ends.  The counters are updated by the 250Hz NMI.\r\n\r\nBecause AUDFn and AUDCn are specified by different chunks, care must be taken to ensure the durations run out at the same time.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"12230":{
"Text":"\r\nSome data used by self test.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"409":{
"Text":"Update projectile positions and check for collisions.  To avoid having fast-moving projectiles fly through things, we advance them four steps per frame and check for collisions after each step.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4380":{
"Text":"Update score for saucer strike.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4409":{
"Text":"\r\nObstacle diameters, for projectile collision detection.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4262":{
"Text":"Projectile struck obstacle.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4354":{
"Text":"Projectile struck saucer.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4135":{
"Text":"Play an explosion sound.  It\u0027s soft for the owner of the projectile and loud for the unit that got hit, so two values are updated.  The enemy unit can\u0027t actually hear, so the value written to $17 isn\u0027t used.\r\n\r\n(This could be written with less code.  Possibly done this way to support a head-to-head 2-player mode.)\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1508":{
"Text":"Update discrete sounds.  The value in $15 holds the bits for cannon volume, explosion volume, and engine rev up/down.  The bits for actually playing cannon and explosion sounds are set here, based on countdown timers.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1551":{
"Text":"Play a sound if a slam was detected.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"7270":{
"Text":"\r\nUpdates position of both projectiles.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"266":{
"Text":"Authenticity check.  Stores the value 1 in $02ed.  Computes a checksum on the drawing commands, which (since we\u0027re not playing) should start with the copyright notice.  Anything but 0 or 1 causes saucer sounds to be suppressed after 100K points.  (See also $526c.)",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"289":{
"Text":"Draw status text messages.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"13628":{
"Text":"Radar frame and vision code.  Leaves beam at center of radar.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"13672":{
"Text":"Tank icon, indicates number of lives left.  Also used in high score list.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6590":{
"Text":"\r\nCreates a new enemy unit.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6725":{
"Text":"\r\nCommon code for creating a new tank or missile.\r\n\r\nThe caller passes an angle adjustment in.  The value is added to the player\u0027s facing to determine the angle at which the new unit will appear.  Small values will put the enemy unit to the front, while large values will put it to the sides or rear.\r\n\r\nWe want the enemy unit to be within vision / radar range, so we need to ensure it\u0027s between the near and far planes ($03ff-7aff).\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: enemy angle adjustment\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6845":{
"Text":"Use the X/Z values to set the enemy unit\u0027s position as an offset from the player\u0027s current position.  There\u0027s no test here for collision with an obstacle.  (Are the obstacles placed in a way that prevents this?)\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2552":{
"Text":"Add treads and spinning radar.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2538":{
"Text":"Add missile splatter.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2742":{
"Text":"\r\nAdd saucer to visible objects list.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2847":{
"Text":"\r\nFinish View transform and test visibility against the sides and \"far\" plane.\r\n\r\nCall after invoking math box function $0b.  Called for 5 different categories of things: enemy unit, projectiles, saucer, obstacles, enemy unit chunks.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  Y-reg: offset of next entry in visible object list\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  Y-reg: incremented by two iff object added to list\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4623":{
"Text":"Joysticks are low four bits, LLRR: 00=middle, 10=fwd, 01=back.  After inversion, 11=middle, 01=fwd, 10=back.  Because 00 is not a valid value, the smallest possible value is 0101 = 5.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4880":{
"Text":"\r\nCalculate the X/Z components of forward motion for the player or enemy tank.  (Missiles use a different function.)\r\n\r\nThis takes the high byte of the cos/sin values and multiplies by 3/4, yielding a maximum distance of $60 (96).  The actual values may be slightly off due to approximations and rounding.  For example, if you\u0027re driving straight toward +X, the cosine value will be $7fff which becomes $5e.\r\n\r\nFurther, this doesn\u0027t handle divide-by-two of signed integers correctly (should inc before shift if negative), so off-by-one errors are possible depending on facing.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: $00 (player) or $02 (enemy)\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  $19/1a: delta Z (signed 16-bit value)\r\n  $1d/1e: delta X (signed 16-bit value)\r\n  X-reg preserved\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4721":{
"Text":"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4767":{
"Text":"Check to see if player wants to fire the cannon.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5585":{
"Text":"Shoot at player.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"164":{
"Text":"Generate list of visible objects.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"616":{
"Text":"\r\nIf not playing the game, perform an authenticity check.  This is only called while we\u0027re showing the battlefield in \"attract\" mode, which generally means that the copyright notice is being rendered.  (I think it\u0027s drawn first, which would make this a check on the copyright string.)\r\n\r\nIf we\u0027re currently showing the logo, this continues to the code that adds the logo to the visible object list.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"170":{
"Text":"Transform and draw all objects in the visible-objects list.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4018":{
"Text":"We want to compare the distance between the unit and the projectile against the radius of the unit.  Units aren\u0027t circular, so facing matters.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3093":{
"Text":"Assign the chunk object type.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4560":{
"Text":"\r\nUpdates the player\u0027s position, based on controller reads (if playing) or timing (if in attract mode).\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"423":{
"Text":"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2921":{
"Text":"Object is visible, add it to the list.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3863":{
"Text":"\r\nComputes sin(theta), where theta is a 9-bit value.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: angle upper 8 bits ($00-ff)\r\n  A-reg: angle LSB ($00/$01)\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  A-reg: sine value, low byte\r\n  X-reg: sine value, high byte\r\n  Y-reg preserved\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3833":{
"Text":"\r\nComputes cos(theta), where theta is a 9-bit value.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: angle upper 8 bits ($00-ff)\r\n  A-reg: angle LSB ($00/$01)\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  A-reg: sine value, low byte\r\n  X-reg: sine value, high byte\r\n  Y-reg preserved\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3890":{
"Text":"Interpolate first result with what\u0027s in A-reg/X-reg.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2374":{
"Text":"\r\nGenerates the visibility list.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2376":{
"Text":"Start by setting R0/R1/R2/R3 to the player\u0027s position and facing.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2504":{
"Text":"Copy position and facing for accessory objects (drip/tread) from index 0 to index 2.  This is wasted for the super tank, which has no add-ons.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2595":{
"Text":"Antenna is placed off-center on slow tank.  Position it.  If you look at the data at $3955, you\u0027ll see that the antenna mount is at Z=-512 X=0 Y=80.  Model X/Z coordinates are 2x world, so we want to place the object at Z=-256.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2668":{
"Text":"\r\nAdd projectiles to visible object list.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"2888":{
"Text":"We\u0027ve computed X/Z and determined that the object is between the near and far planes.  Now check left/right.  (Remember that +X is to the left.)\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"7470":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws the current score, high score, and displays the number of lives left.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1570":{
"Text":"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"7076":{
"Text":"Player out of range of enemy.  If it\u0027s a missile, we kill it and make a new unit.  If it\u0027s a tank we keep going.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6889":{
"Text":"\r\nDraws the radar at the top of the screen.\r\n\r\nAlso, if a missile misses the player and gets too far away, this spawns a new one.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6911":{
"Text":"Compute the screen coordinates of the end of the beam.  In a Cartesian plane angle 0 is toward the right (+X), but we want to have angle 0 at the top (+Y), so everything needs to be rotated 90 degrees.  We also want it to rotate clockwise rather than CCW.  We can do this trivially by flipping the equation, using X=sin(theta) and Y=cos(theta).\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6994":{
"Text":"See if radar scan will sweep over enemy this frame.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11230":{
"Text":"The 255 addresses we didn\u0027t set are all zero.  Now verify that the address we set hasn\u0027t changed.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11332":{
"Text":"\r\nTest RAM from $100-3ff and $2000-3fff.  Now that we know zero page RAM is working we can use pointers.\r\n\r\nThere are 5 pairs of RAM chips.  Each pair holds 1K of memory:\r\n  0/1: $0000-03ff\r\n  2/3: $2000-23ff\r\n  4/5: $2400-27ff\r\n  6/7: $2800-2bff\r\n  8/9: $2c00-2fff\r\n\r\nOne chip in each pair holds the low 4 bits, the other holds the high 4 bits.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11393":{
"Text":"Play failed RAM test tone.  As noted earlier, play 1-10 tones, with short/low for good and long/high for bad.  We play tones for both chips in a pair, stopping at the bad pair.\r\n\r\nAt this point, A-reg has failed value, Y-reg has byte offset.\r\n\r\nBug here: if there\u0027s a fault in low RAM ($0000-03ff), the error is mis-reported.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11580":{
"Text":"\r\nMath box test.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11774":{
"Text":"Atari service manual: \"If ROM or PROM B/C3 is bad, you will hear a continuous low tone, and the program may be unable to display a screen image.\"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11784":{
"Text":"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11449":{
"Text":"Play the first tone for a bit.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11471":{
"Text":"Pause briefly.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11792":{
"Text":"Pause for a bit.  We can\u0027t use the NMI for timing, so this is how we pace the display refresh.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11815":{
"Text":"Draw some stuff on the screen, using the game routines.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"12234":{
"Text":"\r\nCommands for VSM test sequence.  For each of 4 tests, the code gets the length in bytes from the length table, and then copies that many bytes (minus one) to $2010.  A HALT instruction is added to the end of the sequence.\r\n\r\nAmong other things, the test confirms that a four-deep VSJR works.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11861":{
"Text":"Add commands for VSM test #X, where X is 0-3.  The first test is a fat diagonal line from the bottom left to the top right, the rest add on to it.  At this point the pointer in $02 is $2010.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"12158":{
"Text":"\r\nFifth stage of the \"diag step\" sequence.  Exercises all I/O and math box functions.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11989":{
"Text":"Display any failed ROM checksums.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"12043":{
"Text":"If the math box failed, show the failure code.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"12104":{
"Text":"Check coin activity.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"12086":{
"Text":"Make sounds when joysticks are moved, buttons are pressed, or coins are inserted.  One tone is made when the button is pressed, a different tone when the button is released.  A count of the number of selected inputs is kept so we know which sound to make.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6162":{
"Text":"Compute abs(player_x - enemy_x).",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6308":{
"Text":"Look up the angle in the table.  This is limited to one octant; we use the signs to determine the quadrant and whether we did X/Z or Z/X to determine the octant.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6320":{
"Text":"Take the collected sign bits and use them to choose the correct quadrant.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3062":{
"Text":"Modify the velocity further, and rotate the chunk.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3140":{
"Text":"Check to see if all chunks have hit the ground.  If so, create a new enemy unit.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6491":{
"Text":"Now check for a collision between the enemy unit and the player.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"10777":{
"Text":"\r\nAppends a VRTS instruction to the command list.  Unused.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"7117":{
"Text":"Compute the screen coordinates at which we want to draw the blip.  We\u0027re effectively using polar coordinates: R4L (the object Z coordinate) was set to the distance, R5 (the object X coordinate) is set to zero, and the angle to the enemy is in $a6.\r\n\r\n(Could we use the position from the visible object list instead of calculating it here?)\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4975":{
"Text":"\r\nMoves the unit backward.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: $00 for player, $02 for enemy unit\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4945":{
"Text":"\r\nMoves the unit forward.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: $00 for player, $02 for enemy unit\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4948":{
"Text":"\r\nMoves the unit by a specified amount.  Ignores facing.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: $00 for player, $02 for enemy unit\r\n  $19/1a: delta Z\r\n  $1d/1e: delta X\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5005":{
"Text":"\r\nRotates the unit to the left.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: $00 for player, $02 for enemy unit\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5019":{
"Text":"\r\nRotates the unit to the left.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  X-reg: $00 for player, $02 for enemy unit\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"799":{
"Text":"\r\nInitializes some logo-display parameters and the frame counters.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11165":{
"Text":"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"8840":{
"Text":"\r\nGerman strings.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"8438":{
"Text":"\r\nSpanish strings.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"7994":{
"Text":"\r\nFrench strings.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"7571":{
"Text":"\r\nEnglish strings.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"13714":{
"Text":"Shattered windshield effects, in 8 parts.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"16375":{
"Text":"\r\nObject types for logo display.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"16381":{
"Text":"\r\nUnused bytes.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6690":{
"Text":"\r\nCreates a missile.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6670":{
"Text":"Get a value from $00-78 that affects the angle at which the enemy unit is placed.  Smaller values place the enemy closer to where the player is facing, so we use those when we\u0027re being nice.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6796":{
"Text":"Now repeat the process for sin(angle) and the X coordinate.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6741":{
"Text":"Compute the Z coordinate using cos(angle).",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6632":{
"Text":"\r\nCreates a new enemy tank.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"720":{
"Text":"Three-part logo starts at $fc00 (center point below ground), with the 3rd \"Zone\" object mostly behind us.  We don\u0027t want to start drawing \"Zone\" until it has progressed a little bit.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"9941":{
"Text":"\r\nBattlezone logo.  This is split into 3 pieces because the way meshes are defined prevents us from having more than 32 vertices per object.  The logo has 61, so we could fit it into two, but it\u0027s a bit easier for the humans if we split it at a natural boundary.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4792":{
"Text":"Configure projectile velocity.  We use the sin/cos value ($0000-ffff) right-shifted 7x with sign-extension ($0000-00ff or $ffff-ff00).  Projectiles move 4x per frame, so with a time-to-live of $7f, the maximum distance traveled is 256*127=32512 ($7f00), which is a bit past the \"far\" plane (even if moving forward?).  The range is slightly shorter when the player is shooting down an axis because the sin/cos table doesn\u0027t represent 1.0 precisely.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4831":{
"Text":"Now do the same for sin(value).",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"4863":{
"Text":"Finally, set the projectile\u0027s position equal to the player\u0027s position.  It won\u0027t actually be visible until it passes the \"near\" plane.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5144":{
"Text":"\r\nUpdates the position and movement strategy of the enemy unit.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  $2c: angle to player\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5525":{
"Text":"\r\nAttempts to shoot the player.  Does not fire if the the player or enemy is newly-spawned, if the angle is too large, or the relative scores indicate that we should be mellow.\r\n\r\nOn exit if we thought about taking a shot:\r\n  $08/09: abs(deltaZ)\r\n  $0a/0b: abs(deltaX)\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5599":{
"Text":"Configure projectile velocity.  We use the sin/cos value ($0000-ffff) right-shifted 7x with sign-extension (+/-255).  Projectiles move 4x per frame.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5624":{
"Text":"Repeat for sin(angle).",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5649":{
"Text":"Copy enemy unit position to projectile.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5824":{
"Text":"Move the missile forward in the direction it\u0027s currently facing.  We take the sin/cos values ($0000-ffff) and right-shift them 6x with sign extension (+/-512), which is easiest to do by shifting a byte right and then 2 bits left.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5758":{
"Text":"Check the score to see if missiles should be nastier, which happens at 25K points beyond the initial missile threshold.  In this context, \"nasty\" determines how far the missile is from the player when it stops swerving.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5851":{
"Text":"Repeat for cos(angle).",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5880":{
"Text":"Copy the current position to $c0-c3 (same as CopyPosToC0).",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6012":{
"Text":"\r\nUpdates the saucer position and velocity.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"6549":{
"Text":"\r\nCollision radii for obstacle vs. player or enemy unit.\r\n\r\nCompare to the obstacle vs. projectile table at $6139.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5668":{
"Text":"\r\nUpdates the position and movement pattern of a missile.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5067":{
"Text":"\r\nUpdates the move counter and \"close\" firing angle.  This code seems like it was intended to do more than it actually does.  Only used for tanks.\r\n\r\nThis is only called with $00 when the enemy is out-scoring the player.\r\n\r\nOn entry:\r\n  A-reg: $00 for long movements, $80 for short movements\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  A-reg/X-reg/Y-reg preserved\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5121":{
"Text":"I\u0027m not sure what this code is trying to accomplish.  What it actually does is cause $CF to alternate between $02 and $10.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5489":{
"Text":"The enemy is out-scoring the player (e.g. the very first tank killed the player), so we\u0027re going to be very kind.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5425":{
"Text":"Tanks don\u0027t back up when they hit a player.  The tactic that involves running at a tank and shooting it while it turns to face doesn\u0027t work because of the collision, it works because the player is suddenly at an angle that causes the enemy tank to switch from \"move forward\" to \"rotate\".",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5173":{
"Text":"We\u0027re backing up.  While doing so we also rotate to the left or right.  When done, we drive forward for a few seconds.  The player\u0027s position does not factor into any of this movement.\r\n\r\nNote no collision detection is performed, which allows tanks that spawn inside obstacles to back out of them.  This would also allow tanks to back up onto the player, but that\u0027s pretty hard to set up.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5156":{
"Text":"\r\nUpdates the position and movement strategy of an enemy tank.\r\n\r\nThe game puts a target angle in $bc, and moves toward it for a few frames.  In the early game we pick angles away from the player and chase them for a few seconds, but once the game gets going we head directly at the player.\r\n\r\nBecause we move toward an angle that isn\u0027t updated every frame, distant tanks will exhibit a somewhat jerky forward-rotate-forward-rotate movement style.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5428":{
"Text":"\r\nThe move counter expired.  Pick a new direction to move toward.  If we\u0027re being nice we\u0027ll drive a bit randomly, but once the game gets going we just use the angle to the player.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5219":{
"Text":"Rotate toward the facing in $bc, moving forward if we\u0027re pointed toward the player and not too close.  If the facing is within a few degrees of the player\u0027s position, fire the cannon.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5236":{
"Text":"Angle is too large, rotate without moving forward.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5298":{
"Text":"The angle is nearly correct.  Turn slowly (so we don\u0027t overshoot) and move forward if we\u0027re not right in the player\u0027s face.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5358":{
"Text":"Move toward the player.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5459":{
"Text":"After a recent rez the player is winning, but just barely.  Pick an off-target angle.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5513":{
"Text":"Head directly at player.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5938":{
"Text":"Restore position from $c0-c3 (same as CopyPosFromC0).",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5799":{
"Text":"Make the missile zig-zag.\r\n\r\nThe big swerves aren\u0027t done by changing the missile\u0027s desired direction -- the small rotations performed earlier update the desired facing to match changes in the position of the player and the missile.  The big swerves are done by setting the missile\u0027s facing to an angle offset from the desired angle.\r\n\r\nThe amount of swerve is determined by the low 5 bits of the game frame counter, which cycle in the span of 2 seconds.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"207":{
"Text":"Set a couple of angles used in enemy movement code.\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"226":{
"Text":"Draw reticle.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"546":{
"Text":"Spawn the player in a random location.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3218":{
"Text":"Moves to the vertex and draws a point.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3231":{
"Text":"Set intensity with vertex index value (overridden for saucer/logo).",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3284":{
"Text":"Moves to center of screen, then moves without drawing.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3297":{
"Text":"Moves without drawing.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3301":{
"Text":"Draws to vertex with global intensity.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3309":{
"Text":"Draws projectile explosion.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3342":{
"Text":"No-op.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"3393":{
"Text":"Advances the shape code pointer, then jumps to the top of the object draw loop.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"5961":{
"Text":"Missile and player collided.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"14182":{
"Text":"Another self-test pattern.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"14212":{
"Text":"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"14469":{
"Text":"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11827":{
"Text":"\r\nDraw lines for the VSM test.  Activated by the diag step switch.\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"12217":{
"Text":"\r\nChecks to see if the diag step input has been grounded (switch pressed).\r\n\r\nOn exit:\r\n  A-reg: $20 if input grounded but wasn\u0027t before\r\n  P-flags set according to A-reg\r\n\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1771":{
"Text":"Check the slam switch.",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"1795":{
"Text":"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0},

"11343":{
"Text":"\r\n",
"BoxMode":false,
"MaxWidth":80,
"BackgroundColor":0}},

